posts.cooked: I have been trying to load some ProtobufLogEntry data logs, but the entries are only 8 bytes long and fail to parse. In advantage scope, the entry is visible and accurate so I know it is logging correctly. When printing out the bytes it always gives 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, -44, -40, 63, but the type is still correct. Does anybody know the issue or have an example of successful protobuf log reading I can look at?

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked:
Thanks for checking with AdvantageScope to verify the logged values are correct.

What you are seeing is the raw encoded bytes.  At least in wpilib, we don’t currently have generic library support for decoding protobuf encoded log entries.  Decoding requires a protobuf library; reading the contents of the logged /.schema/ value corresponding to the data type gives the Protobuf schema that can be given to the library for dynamic decoding of the Protobuf raw data back into a more complex data structure.
I have the protobuf library, the issue is the entry just doesn’t contain all the data. It should contain 100+ bytes, but only contains the same 8 for every entry.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: But AdvantageScope sees the data fine from the same log file?  I’m clearly missing something.  How are you reading the log entry data?

I am reading the entry with the data log reader. I get the iterator from the data log reader and call next until there is no data. Once I get the start entry I log the ID and then any further DataLogRecords with the ID are added to a map. I have verified it is loading the correct entry, the type is correct, and the timestamp is changing. I have attached the log below. I renamed it with the extension txt, so if you open it you might want to rename it to wpilog. FRC_20250316_205358_GAGWI_E15.txt (35.8 MB)
I should add that the entry I am trying to load is the Vision/ScoringOV9281_result or the equivalent proto stored in the nt logs.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Are you using the Java reader or the Python one?  There may be a bug in the Java reader implementation, or at least unexpected behavior, due to the way it slices ByteBuffer.
I am using the java one. I will try to create a test project and share it here.

I take back what I said about the network tables results, they do not appear to be working how I thought they were. My code seems to be incorrect somewhere in between the log loading and the printing because it seems to be loading fine in the test project. Probably should have made the example project first, but thank you for your time.
